            <div type="glosses" subtype="textual">
                <note xml:id="JUSTIFICATION" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">Justification mark (MS IX)&#x2014;</hi>See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="editorial_rationale_note.php#JUSTIFICATION">Editorial and Encoding Rationale and Methodology: Element, Attribute, and Value Usage&#x2014;Justification, Runover, and Word Division</ref>.</p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="GETIN" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x0201C;get in&#x0201D; (<hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;</hi>The editors of the 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="library_edition_note.html">Library Edition</ref> 
                    inserted &#x201C;(<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>)&#x201D; here, presumably objecting to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s choice of preposition, 
                    but they did not tamper with the parallelism that he evidently intended in this series of predicate adjective phrases
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:345).</p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="WORDDIVISIONBURNING" resp="#DCH"><p>In <title type="manuscript" corresp="MSIX">MS IX</title>, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> omitted a hyphen to indicate that the syllables of <hi rend="italic">burning</hi> are divided between lines.</p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="GAVETOLIFE" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x0201C;gave to life&#x0201D; (MS IX; <hi rend="italic">Works</hi> [1903])&#x2014;</hi>The editors of the 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="library_edition_note.html">Library Edition</ref> 
                    added a note to gloss the meaning of this phrase as &#x201C;gave life to&#x201D;; however, as their restraint suggests, 
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s inversion appears not to be a slip, but what caught his ear 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic"><title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE">Works</title></hi></ref>, 2:345 n. 3).</p></note>
            </div>
